snippet.textDisplay: Recently there is a developing behavioral disconnect between youth Basketball and young rookies lucky enough to be corrected by NBA mentorship in their first year. Even a cursory glance shows the hyping up of games and players in High school and college by crowds and it's SAVAGE taglines for maximum youtube consumption. There are plenty of good reasons to not poke young developing bears. Without more positive intervention by feeder associations and the NCAA inevitably some kids left unchecked will happily do the hyper masculine standover and worse for the reward of clicks, views and the adoration of the hysterical crowd. Some will say a toxic crowd was and will always be there. But does a 13 yr old need to be dipped in hate so early. The NBA is happy to ride the positive effects of this new social media, but they in cooperation with the NCAA need to work harder at curbing its negative effects on younger players and instill a code of respect and empowerment to stand up to the aggression baiting of crowds and social media.
